<td class="" style="padding:0.2em; line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle; font-size:90%;">James and Elizabeth Baumfree</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Sojourner Truth</b> (1797 – November 26, 1883) was the self-given name, from 1843, of <b>Isabella Baumfree</b>, an American slave, <a href="/wiki/Abolitionism" title="Abolitionism">abolitionist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_rights" title="Women's rights">women's rights</a> activist. Truth was born into <a href="/wiki/Slavery" title="Slavery">slavery</a> in <a href="/wiki/Swartekill,_New_York" title="Swartekill, New York" class="mw-redirect">Swartekill</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York" title="New York">New York</a>. Her best-known speech, <a href="/wiki/Ain%27t_I_a_Woman%3F" title="Ain't I a Woman?">Ain't I a Woman?</a>, was delivered in 1851 at the Ohio Women's Rights Convention in <a href="/wiki/Akron,_Ohio" title="Akron, Ohio">Akron, Ohio</a>.</p>
