<li><a href="http://www.newpaltz.edu/sojourner_truth/" class="external text" title="http://www.newpaltz.edu/sojourner_truth/" rel="nofollow">On the trail of Sojourner Truth</a> <a href="/wiki/SUNY_New_Paltz" title="SUNY New Paltz" class="mw-redirect">SUNY New Paltz</a> Sojourner Truth Library</li>
<li><a href="http://www.sojournertruth.org/Default.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.sojournertruth.org/Default.htm" rel="nofollow">Sojourner Truth Institute</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.womenwriters.net/domesticgoddess/truth.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.womenwriters.net/domesticgoddess/truth.htm" rel="nofollow">Poem</a> form of <a href="/wiki/Ar%27n%27t_I_a_Woman%3F" title="Ar'n't I a Woman?" class="mw-redirect">Ain't I a Woman?</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.learningtogive.org/papers/index.asp?bpid=129" class="external text" title="http://www.learningtogive.org/papers/index.asp?bpid=129" rel="nofollow">bio</a> at <a href="/wiki/Indiana_University-Purdue_University_Indianapolis" title="Indiana University-Purdue University Indianapolis">Indiana University-Purdue University Indianapolis</a> <i>Learning to Give</i> site</li>
<li><a href="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth50/menu.html" class="external text" title="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth50/menu.html" rel="nofollow">Narrative of Sojourner Truth, a Northern Slave, Emancipated from Bodily Servitude by the State of New York, in 1828.</a> Boston: The Author, 1850.</li>
<li><a href="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth75/menu.html" class="external text" title="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth75/menu.html" rel="nofollow">Narrative of Sojourner Truth; a Bondswoman of Olden Time, Emancipated by the New York Legislature in the Early Part of the Present Century; with a History of Her Labors and Correspondence, Drawn from Her "Book of Life"</a> Boston: For the Author, 1875.</li>
<li><a href="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth84/menu.html" class="external text" title="http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/truth84/menu.html" rel="nofollow">Narrative of Sojourner Truth; a Bondswoman of Olden Time, Emancipated by the New York Legislature in the Early Part of the Present Century; with a History of Her Labors and Correspondence Drawn from Her "Book of Life;" Also, a Memorial Chapter, Giving the Particulars of Her Last Sickness and Death.</a> Battle Creek, Mich.: Review and Herald Office, 1884.</li>
</ul>
